# linux_abi/api_mac80211.ad
#
# WiFi pivot, leg 2/2: shim closure for the 159 UND symbols Linux's
# stock mac80211.ko (Debian 6.1.0-32 build) consumes beyond what
# L1..L68 + the e1000e/r8169/igb/ahci/nvme/usb/xhci/ehci/cfg80211
# batches already export.
#
# mac80211.ko is the soft-MAC 802.11 stack — it sits between cfg80211
# (admin layer) below and the per-chip drivers (ath9k, iwlwifi, ...)
# above. Every modern wifi driver that doesn't do full hardware MAC
# offload depends on mac80211.
#
# UND analysis (`nm -u mac80211.ko` minus the union of every existing
# linux_abi/api_*.ad export plus api_cfg80211.ad's 50 new exports):
#
#   Group 1 — cfg80211_* cross-module surface                   (72)
#       mac80211 EXTENSIVELY references cfg80211's EXPORT_SYMBOL'd
#       interfaces (cfg80211_scan_done, cfg80211_register_netdevice,
#       cfg80211_*_notify, cfg80211_chandef_*, cfg80211_rx_*, ...).
#       In real Linux these are resolved by load order: cfg80211.ko
#       defines them, mac80211.ko picks them up via the kernel's
#       __ksymtab once cfg80211 is in. Hamnix's loader doesn't yet
#       register module-side EXPORT_SYMBOL exports — so for the .ko
#       relocation pass to resolve, every cfg80211_* symbol mac80211
#       references must appear in our shim table. Each one is a
#       "succeed without side effect" stub keyed on Linux's contract
#       (most return void; some return 0 / NULL).
#
#   Group 2 — ieee80211_* cfg80211-defined helpers              (18)
#       ieee80211_hdrlen, ieee80211_get_channel_khz, ieee80211_data_
#       to_8023_exthdr, ... These are pure utility functions defined
#       in cfg80211 (net/wireless/util.c, chan.c, scan.c). Same
#       cross-module-resolution constraint as Group 1; same shim
#       approach. The radiotap iterator and freq/channel conversion
#       helpers get small real implementations because they're called
#       at probe time.
#
#   Group 3 — wiphy_* work helpers                              (11)
#       wiphy_work_queue / cancel / flush + wiphy_delayed_work_*. The
#       cfg80211 wiphy struct carries an embedded "work cookie" the
#       driver schedules deferred work against. We forward to no-op
#       slots — the deferred work never fires (no kthread dispatch
#       wired through cfg80211's wiphy_work).
#
#   Group 4 — rhashtable                                         (6)
#       rhashtable_init / free_and_destroy / insert_slow,
#       rhltable_init, rht_bucket_nested (+ __ variant),
#       rht_bucket_nested_insert. Linux's resizable hash table for
#       station + scan tables. Stub init returns 0 (success); inserts
#       return -ENOMEM so the caller falls back to a linear search
#       path that doesn't exist in mac80211 init.
#
#   Group 5 — crypto + arc4                                      (5)
#       crypto_alloc_aead / alloc_skcipher / shash_setkey / shash_
#       digest / shash_finup, arc4_crypt / arc4_setkey. Used for the
#       wifi crypto offload paths (CCMP/GCMP/TKIP). Stubs at init
#       time — never invoked until a station joins.
#
#   Group 6 — skb gap-fillers                                    (9)
#       kfree_skb_list_reason, skb_clone_sk, skb_complete_wifi_ack,
#       skb_copy / skb_copy_expand, __skb_get_hash, __skb_gso_segment,
#       skb_queue_head, skb_queue_purge. Augments the existing
#       sk_buff API from api_e1000e / api_l55. All are runtime helpers
#       that never fire at init.
#
#   Group 7 — workqueue / tasklet / timer                        (6)
#       round_jiffies_relative, round_jiffies_up, __usecs_to_jiffies,
#       tasklet_kill, tasklet_unlock_wait, system_freezable_wq (DATA).
#       Mirror the round_jiffies / tasklet surface from api_e1000e
#       and api_misc.
#
#   Group 8 — netdev + hw_addr_list                              (6)
#       __hw_addr_init / sync / unsync, dev_alloc_name,
#       netdev_set_default_ethtool_ops, netif_receive_skb,
#       netif_receive_skb_list. Bookkeeping helpers for the MAC
#       address filter list and a couple of generic netdev hooks.
#
#   Group 9 — bitmap / percpu / idr / find_first_*               (10)
#       __alloc_percpu_gfp, bitmap_free, bitmap_zalloc, _find_first_
#       bit, _find_first_zero_bit, idr_find, idr_for_each, kernel_
#       param_lock, kernel_param_unlock, ktime_get_seconds. Pure
#       library utilities — most have one-line implementations.
#
#   Group 10 — bpf_trace_run4..6 + __x86_indirect_thunk_rbp      (4)
#       The lower-arity bpf_trace_run set (4/5/6) is shared with
#       api_cfg80211.ad; mac80211 ALSO references it, so we let
#       api_cfg80211's exports stand (already registered when
#       linux_abi_register_cfg80211 runs first). __x86_indirect_
#       thunk_rbp is the rbp-variant retpoline — same shape as
#       api_lib80211's __x86_indirect_thunk_rax.
#
#   Group 11 — misc and DATA                                     (12)
#       bridge_tunnel_header (DATA), freq_reg_info, kmalloc_large,
#       kvmalloc_node, led_trigger_blink, regulatory_pre_cac_allowed,
#       rfc1042_header (DATA), system_freezable_wq (DATA).
#
# Stub philosophy: same as cfg80211 / e1000e / xhci pivots — init
# must return 0; runtime calls are deferred until a wifi driver
# materialises on top.
#
# The "_mac_" prefix marks Hamnix-side shims for this batch.

from linux_abi.exports import _add_export
from mm.slab import kmalloc, kzalloc, kfree
from arch.x86.kernel.time import jiffies


# =====================================================================
# DATA buffers for symbols the loader needs an address for
# =====================================================================

# bridge_tunnel_header / rfc1042_header: two well-known LLC SNAP
# headers (each 8 bytes). Real Linux defines them as `const u8[8]`.
# We give them the canonical bit patterns so any read returns the
# correct constant byte sequence.

# rfc1042_header[] = { 0xaa, 0xaa, 0x03, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00 }; (6 bytes
# but kept in an 8-byte slot for alignment with how mac80211 reads it).
_mac_rfc1042_header_buf: Array[8, uint8]

# bridge_tunnel_header[] = { 0xaa, 0xaa, 0x03, 0x00, 0x00, 0xf8 };
_mac_bridge_tunnel_header_buf: Array[8, uint8]

# system_freezable_wq: workqueue *. Same NULL-slot treatment as
# system_unbound_wq in api_cfg80211 — any queue_work against it
# becomes a no-op via the NULL pool path.
_mac_system_freezable_wq_var: uint64 = 0


def _mac_init_data_buffers():
    # Called once from linux_abi_register_mac80211. Populates the
    # rfc1042 + bridge tunnel header bytes that some encap fast-paths
    # would dereference if exercised.
    _mac_rfc1042_header_buf[0] = 0xaa
    _mac_rfc1042_header_buf[1] = 0xaa
    _mac_rfc1042_header_buf[2] = 0x03
    _mac_rfc1042_header_buf[3] = 0x00
    _mac_rfc1042_header_buf[4] = 0x00
    _mac_rfc1042_header_buf[5] = 0x00
    _mac_rfc1042_header_buf[6] = 0x00
    _mac_rfc1042_header_buf[7] = 0x00

    _mac_bridge_tunnel_header_buf[0] = 0xaa
    _mac_bridge_tunnel_header_buf[1] = 0xaa
    _mac_bridge_tunnel_header_buf[2] = 0x03
    _mac_bridge_tunnel_header_buf[3] = 0x00
    _mac_bridge_tunnel_header_buf[4] = 0x00
    _mac_bridge_tunnel_header_buf[5] = 0xf8
    _mac_bridge_tunnel_header_buf[6] = 0x00
    _mac_bridge_tunnel_header_buf[7] = 0x00


